  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we populate the confusion matrix used to visualize the results and use the matrix to determine the overall model accuracy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
    },
    "id": "LBaXWwSwqlkO",
    "outputId": "47458594-017c-4f81-9ba4-19938a4e31c8"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "Overall accuracy: 0.8243\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# === Populating Confusion Matrix and Overall Model Accuracy ===\n",
    "cm = np.zeros((num_classes, num_classes), dtype=int)\n",
    "for t, p in zip(y_true, y_pred):\n",
    "    cm[t, p] += 1\n",
    "\n",
    "accuracy = np.trace(cm) / np.sum(cm) # Model accuracy is diagonal count in confusion matrix divided by total\n",
    "print(f\"\\nOverall accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Overall, the best acheived model accuracy was found to be about 83%"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we consider the remaining statistical values of:\n",
    "*   Sensitivity\n",
    "*   Specificity\n",
    "*   Precision\n",
    "*   F1 Score\n",
    "\n",
    "Per each class and some additional global model metrics"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
    },
    "id": "6JZk-l16qoWr",
    "outputId": "83e2a2c2-7168-4a29-f32c-186c03475734"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "Per-class metrics:\n",
      " Black | Sens=0.725  Spec=0.925  Prec=0.711  F1=0.718  Support=695\n",
      "  Blue | Sens=0.823  Spec=0.922  Prec=0.831  F1=0.827  Support=1086\n",
      " Green | Sens=0.929  Spec=0.969  Prec=0.902  F1=0.915  Support=799\n",
      " other | Sens=0.809  Spec=0.948  Prec=0.836  F1=0.822  Support=852\n",
      "\n",
      "Macro averages (mean over classes):\n",
      "Sensitivity (Recall): 0.821\n",
      "Specificity:          0.941\n",
      "F1:                   0.821\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# === Overall and per Class Model Stats ===\n",
    "eps = 1e-12  # avoid divide-by-zero\n",
    "\n",
    "TP = np.diag(cm)\n",
    "FP = cm.sum(axis=0) - TP\n",
    "FN = cm.sum(axis=1) - TP\n",
    "TN = cm.sum() - (TP + FP + FN)\n",
    "\n",
    "sensitivity = TP / (TP + FN + eps)      # recall / TPR\n",
    "specificity = TN / (TN + FP + eps)      # TNR\n",
    "precision   = TP / (TP + FP + eps)\n",
    "f1          = 2 * precision * sensitivity / (precision + sensitivity + eps)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nPer-class metrics:\")\n",
    "for i, name in enumerate(plot_class_names):\n",
    "    print(f\"{name:>6} | \"\n",
    "          f\"Sens={sensitivity[i]:.3f}  \"\n",
    "          f\"Spec={specificity[i]:.3f}  \"\n",
    "          f\"Prec={precision[i]:.3f}  \"\n",
    "          f\"F1={f1[i]:.3f}  \"\n",
    "          f\"Support={cm.sum(axis=1)[i]}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nMacro averages (mean over classes):\")\n",
    "print(f\"Sensitivity (Recall): {sensitivity.mean():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Specificity:          {specificity.mean():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"F1:                   {f1.mean():.3f}\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Green class exhibits the strongest performance across all metrics, with the highest sensitivity, specificity, and F1-score. This indicates that Green items are both reliably detected and rarely confused with other categories, suggesting strong separability in the learned feature space.\n",
    "\n",
    "In contrast, the Black class demonstrates the weakest performance, with the lowest sensitivity and precision. This implies both frequent misclassification of true Black items and substantial confusion from other classes being predicted as Black. The relatively poor separability of this class suggests significant feature overlap with other waste categories.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Blue class exhibits moderate recall and precision, indicating that a meaningful fraction of Blue items are confused with other categories, though predictions labeled as Blue are generally reliable.\n",
    "\n",
    "The TTR class, while not the weakest performer, may act as a semantically broad category. Given the heterogeneous nature of items assigned to TTR, the network may map uncertain samples into this class when decision boundaries between other categories are ambiguous.\n",
    "\n",
    "Notably, the confusion patterns reflect intuitive human difficulty in waste sorting, where certain categories (e.g., Green) are visually well-defined, while others (particularly Black) exhibit greater ambiguity."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we move onto plotting the confusion matrix."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
     "height": 607
    },
    "id": "6zet0bCAqrDP",
    "outputId": "77d6bd34-1ccd-454f-c03f-8b95fe787437"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# === Plotting Confusion Matrix ===\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))\n",
    "plt.imshow(cm)\n",
    "plt.title(\"Confusion Matrix\")\n",
    "plt.xticks(range(num_classes), plot_class_names, rotation=45, ha=\"right\")\n",
    "plt.yticks(range(num_classes), plot_class_names)\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Predicted\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"True\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# annotate counts\n",
    "for i in range(num_classes):\n",
    "    for j in range(num_classes):\n",
    "        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j], ha=\"center\", va=\"center\")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The confusion matrix highlights clear differences in class separability. The Green class appears to be the most distinct category, with the majority of Green samples correctly classified and comparatively few being assigned to other classes. This indicates that the model has learned strong visual and/or semantic features that reliably distinguish Green items from the rest.\n",
    "\n",
    "In contrast, the most significant confusion occurs between the Black and Blue classes. There is a pronounced bidirectional mix-up between these two categories, with many Black items predicted as Blue and many Blue items predicted as Black. This mutual confusion suggests substantial feature overlap in the learned representation. The items in these classes may share similar textures, materials, or visual characteristics, and their associated textual features may not provide sufficiently discriminative information. As a result, the decision boundary between Black and Blue appears less well-defined than for other class pairs.\n",
    "\n",
    "The TTR class exhibits moderate confusion with multiple other categories, which is consistent with its role as a broad or heterogeneous class. Because TTR may contain a wide variety of visually dissimilar items, the model can occasionally map ambiguous samples into or out of this category. However, confusion between TTR and Green appears comparatively limited, further reinforcing the distinctiveness of the Green class.\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, the confusion matrix suggests that while the model performs strongly on well-separated categories, it struggles with classes that share overlapping visual or semantic characteristics—particularly Black and Blue. This indicates that further improvements may require more discriminative features, additional training samples, or refined class definitions to better separate these overlapping categories."
   ]
  }
